JOHANNESBURG &#8211; South Africa&#8217;s rand was slightly softer against the advancing dollar on Thursday while stocks followed global peers higher after investors were encouraged by President Donald Trump&#8217;s less combative tone in his first speech to Congress.The rand was 0.12% weaker against dollar, fetching 13.04/dollar at 0705 GMT, as the greenback was supported by growing bets on a US rate hike this month.NKC African Economics pegs the rand range for the day at 12.80-13.20/dollar.The Top-40 index was 0.44% firmer at 44 870, All-share index 0.42% higher at 51 898.Bonds were slightly firmer with yield on benchmark paper due in 2026 1.5 basis points lower to 8.785%.